**10 Heisenberg's Uncertainty Principle**

Heisenberg's Uncertainty Principle states that the product of the uncertainty \(\Delta x\) in the position of a body at any instant and the uncertainty \(\Delta p\) in its momentum at the same instant is greater than or approximately equal to the Planck constant.

\[\Delta x\Delta p\geq\hbar\]

The more precisely one variable is known, the less precisely the other is known. Hence, it is impossible to know the exact speed (mass can be exact) or exact position of an object, as the uncertainty in the other would approach infinity.

One way to think of it as it is impossible to tell the speed of a car from a picture (knowing its position exactly), likewise it is impossible to tell the exact position of a car from a video (knowing its speed exactly).

